<i> So I'm going</i>
<i> to the power hammer.</i>

05:04.096 --> 05:05.929
<i> I've never worked</i>
<i> with it before,</i>

05:05.973 --> 05:07.889
so it's probably gonna be
a love-hate relationship.

05:07.933 --> 05:10.350
It's like, you know, first date,
hey, how you doing?

05:10.394 --> 05:13.061
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

05:13.105 --> 05:14.938
- Ah!

05:14.982 --> 05:17.107
- This might be one of our most
technical challenges.

05:17.151 --> 05:18.817
- I think it is.

05:18.861 --> 05:20.193
- Because not only do they have
to create that guard

05:20.237 --> 05:21.820
<i>with the barrel ring,</i>

05:21.864 --> 05:23.280
<i>they have to account</i>
<i>for the bayonet lug.</i>

05:23.324 --> 05:24.990
<i> - Yep.</i>

05:25.034 --> 05:26.700
<i>- If they don't get that</i>
<i> just right,</i>

05:26.744 --> 05:28.535
then the bayonet will not fit
to the end of the rifle.

05:28.579 --> 05:30.162
- Right.

05:30.205 --> 05:32.831
<i> - I have zero experience</i>
<i> with bayonets.</i>

05:32.875 --> 05:36.585
<i> I have never made a knife</i>
<i> that attaches to a gun.</i>

05:36.628 --> 05:38.295
In here with these
other three guys,

05:38.339 --> 05:40.630
I feel like the old man
of the group,

05:40.674 --> 05:44.343
but I'm not gonna
let these young boys whip me.

05:44.386 --> 05:46.970
- Yeah, there we go. We've got
some teamwork going on.

05:47.014 --> 05:49.097
- I wanted to leave it
the full length

05:49.141 --> 05:51.350
so I can have a handle
to hold rather

05:51.393 --> 05:53.477
than working it with tongs.

05:53.520 --> 05:55.103
When Clarence came over
and helped me

05:55.147 --> 05:57.189
get my spring straightened out,

05:57.232 --> 05:59.649
<i> I realized, even though</i>
<i> this is a competition,</i>

05:59.693 --> 06:02.319
<i> the camaraderie</i>
<i> between the bladesmiths</i>

06:02.363 --> 06:05.280
is a great thing to witness.
Let me help him.

06:05.324 --> 06:07.783
- Some of this stuff that
you're doing is heavy work,

06:07.826 --> 06:09.826
and if you see
somebody struggling,

06:09.870 --> 06:11.620
<i>you're not just gonna sit there</i>
<i> and watch them, you know?</i>

06:11.663 --> 06:14.122
So that's what we do.

06:14.166 --> 06:17.834
I work somewhat intuitively,
definitely letting the material

06:17.878 --> 06:19.503
that I'm working
with speak to me.

06:19.546 --> 06:22.130
My plan for this round
is to straighten this steel out,

06:22.174 --> 06:25.008
get it under the power hammer,
get it shaped.

06:25.052 --> 06:27.094
